                         LANCELOT CONTEST 

Within the Lancelot game was a prize contest to find a solid 
silver grail, encrusted with jewels. It was found on 28/2/89, 
and this sheet contains full details of the contest so that 
you can test your wits against the winner. 


                           FIRST STAGE 

Treasure contests are risky things to design. Some are too 
easy and solved almost instantly (Cadbury's quest for golden 
Easter eggs resulted in some being dug up even before the 
questions were published). And others are too difficult. (One 
pirate quest for a golden key and #50,000 prize has never been 
solved. The organisers say they are snowed under by letters from 
frustrated seekers, and would love to bring it to an end, but 
they can't legally change its terms). 

So I wanted a two stage quest, with four preliminary rounds, one 
per month, each with nine winners to go on to the final. That 
way I would know how long the first stage would take, and could 
adjust the difficulty of the preliminary rounds if we were 
getting too many, or too few, winners. 

The preliminary contests all worked the same way. You 'phoned 
a special Grail Hotline to learn the current starting clue. For 
example, "Welcome to the Grail Hotline. The clue for October is 
a weighty matter". This meant the relevant clue words (all in 
capitals) were those in the same sentence as something to do 
with weight, e.g pound, ounce, ton. You sorted them into a 
description of an Arthurian place, often referring to its 
legends, which they also spelt with their first or last 
letters. In the example, the words are all found around Merlin's 
house, "MERLIN'S GIANT MICRO UPON THE HEATH; THE WELL-KNOWN 
STANDING CIRCLE", and spell "STONEHENGE". 

(When this example was printed in the instructions, a zealous 
proof-reader removed the hyphen! STONEHELNGE? But people coped). 


